[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Writing a book the old-fashioned way is very difficult, even if you\'ve done a lot of it. I personally wrote 14 books the traditional way before burning out hard around 2019, and it was only then that AI came into the picture a few'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'years later, and I realized that not only did it solve my burnout, but if I were to continue writing like I used to, I would be sabotaging myself on purpose. So, in this video, I\'m going to show off my entire AI stack that not only makes'

[00:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it easier to create, but actually allows me to do more than I could have ever done before. Before I get into the first tool, if you\'re one of those people I see in the comments occasionally that says that art should be hard, let me'

[00:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tell you, I used to think the same thing as well. But, I then came to realize that if you think something should be hard, it will be. And if you think something will be easy, it will likely be that, too. The mere act of thinking something should be hard is actually a'

[00:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'form of self-sabotage, or at least it was in my case. Every major leap forward in both my life and my business has come because I\'ve chosen to just chill and take it a little bit easier, and that\'s when energy starts to flow. If you\'re'

[01:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'still doubting, let me ask you this. Are you a creator, or are you the labor? It used to be that creation required some of both, but AI has managed to get to the point where it handles the labor pretty well, but it\'s not so good at the'

[01:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'thinking, the part where actual creation happens in your own mind. And since art has forever been that intersection between the human mind and technology, anyway, I discovered from my own burnout experience that we can actually take a'

[01:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'lot of the headache out by merging the two together. So, let\'s dive in into the tools that I recommend to make your life much easier. The first tool that I recommend for all writers out there is an internet-aware chatbot. Now, most of'

[01:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you are probably thinking, well, this is absolutely nothing new. Why are we even talking about this? But, I have found that I get the most value for most areas of my life from a simple chatbot. This'

[01:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is one of the reasons why ChatGPT exploded when it came onto the scene. It\'s just a darn useful tool. Now, these days, I don\'t recommend ChatGPT. The two that I would recommend to you are'

[02:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Claude, specifically Claude Pro, the $20 subscription, and Perplexity. I would also recommend the $20 subscription for Perplexity. Let me show you a little bit about what they have. Both of them, you can tell it\'s just a very simple chat'

[02:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'interface. They look very similar to each other. The reason I recommend these two is that they are the ones that I think have best cracked the usefulness for just human interaction, the way humans actually need things, and uh integrating into your life and your'

[02:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'office and all of that. I used to recommend Perplexity almost exclusively, because one of the things Perplexity can do, if you see here, I can select a model, and there are multiple models to choose from. Like, if you enjoy the Claude models, you can actually get'

[02:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Claude here inside of Perplexity. But, if you like the GPT models or the Gemini models, you can get those, too. They also have their own proprietary models, and Claude doesn\'t do that. Claude only gives you access to their own models. And, the reason I don\'t recommend'

[02:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Perplexity as much as I used to is because due to their terms of services, you can\'t actually use anything from Perplexity for commercial use. That\'s a big hang-up for me, because here on this channel, we do a lot of writing with AI,'

[03:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a lot of that co-creation, and Perplexity doesn\'t allow you to use that for commercial use. However, if you\'re only going to be using a chatbot for everything non-writing related, cuz when I get to tool number two, we\'ll talk'

[03:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'about something that you\'ll use instead for most of your writing, then Perplexity is absolutely fine. I use it primarily, it\'s my number one chatbot that I use for most of the tasks that I need it to do, mostly regarding'

[03:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'research, as a kind of Google replacement, and various other odds and ends that I need AI for. And, that\'s one of the great things about a chatbot in general is that it\'s a great catch-all for everything that you could possibly'

[03:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'need. It might not be as specialized in any one area or another, but it\'s good enough in almost everything that it can be extremely useful, which is why I recommend it. So, if you don\'t think you\'re going to be using a chatbot for any kind of actual content creation,'

[04:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'then Perplexity is definitely the one for you. If not, I recommend Claude, which tends to be the best one for content creation. I say tends to. It also happens to have a lot of really good integrations with other things, and'

[04:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it\'s connected to the internet just like Perplexity is. Although, I don\'t think it does quite as good of a job that Perplexity does at citing its sources and doing that research quickly and efficiently and all that. Claude is also'

[04:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'known to throttle people, so if you\'re using it a lot, you may be told to come back later. And I\'ve never run into that issue so far on Perplexity, although I think they are clamping down a little bit on some of their usage. So, once you\'ve picked a tool that acts as your'

[04:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'catch-all for everything that you could possibly use, we do need to get some tools that are more specific. So, this leads me to tool number two, which is a writing-specific wrapper tool. And when we say wrapper tool, we\'re talking about a tool that'

[04:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'just harnesses AI in a specific way. And we call that the wrapper. It uses the AI, but it puts a sort of fresh coat of paint on it that is specifically designed for a writing workflow, for a coding workflow, whatever kind of'

[05:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'workflow you\'re looking for that\'s specialized in that thing. For this channel, we are most interested in a writing-specific wrapper tool. And right now, there are three, soon to be four, big ones on the market. The first that I\'m going to talk about is Raptor Write,'

[05:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'which is kind of simple. It doesn\'t do much, but it has the advantage of being free. And it\'s definitely one of the ones that I recommend to a beginner who has no idea where to start, and they just kind of want to play around with something. It is free, although you do'

[05:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'still have to pay for any tokens that are generated inside of the tool, which is true of all but one of the tools on this list. The second one that I recommend is Novel Crafter. Novel Crafter was one of the first out of the gate and one of the most used by a lot'

[05:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of people. I used it myself very heavily before until I switched to something else which I\'ll get to in tool three. But if you are someone that wants hyper control over every single detail of your workflow and have it come together in a'

[05:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'way that\'s pretty seamless, NovelCrafter might be the one for you. However, the only downside of NovelCrafter is of all of the ones on this list, it is probably the one with the highest learning curve. It\'s perhaps the most powerful and most'

[06:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'flexible, but a extremely high learning curve for getting into NovelCrafter. The third wrapper tool that I recommend is Sudowrite. This one\'s a little bit easier. They try to be kind of the Apple of these AI writing tools. The only'

[06:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'issues that I have with them is that they are much more of a closed ecosystem and they\'re kind of clamped down on the way you should do things and there\'s not as much flexibility inside of their platform. Additionally, they have a different pricing model where you\'re not'

[06:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'paying as you go, but you\'re actually paying for credits as you have to use those credits or you lose them. There are some plans where you can keep them. That\'s not going to last forever. So, there are some things about Sudowrite that I don\'t like as much. They did have'

[06:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this tool called Muse. It\'s their own proprietary fine-tuned model that was very, very good when it came out. But these days the moat between that fine-tuned large language model that they have and the other large language models that are coming out just'

[06:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generally and accessible to everyone has kind of been lost. So, they really don\'t have as big of an advantage as they used to. They are also one of the pricier ones on this list. So, it\'s something to look at. A lot of people are really passionate about Sudowrite and I love the the people that work there. I\'ve'

[07:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'worked with them myself several times. But it is one that I would only look at if you don\'t like the other two. Lastly, I do need to make a small confession here in the interest of full transparency. I am actually developing my own tool. In fact, by the time this'

[07:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'goes out, it\'s in open beta for members of my community. Not fully ready to launch yet, but because of that, I can no longer good conscience talk about these tools in a completely unbiased way. As much as I try to, I know that I'

[07:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'cannot actually be fully unbiased when it comes to all of these tools because some skin of my own in the game and adds a small conflict of interest. I\'m not going to show off that tool just yet. I\'m not quite ready for it, but I just'

[07:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'wanted to make sure that was out there and people were aware of it. It is the dream tool that I\'ve been trying to put together that kind of combines the best of a lot of different things and hopefully it\'ll be pretty awesome when you guys get to finally see it. But for'

[08:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'now, let\'s just move on to tool number three which I think is has been the biggest game-changer for me in my life. So, the big one for me, and this is actually what drew me away from using a wrapper specific tool like Novacrafter'

[08:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'or Sudowrite or those others is an automation engine. Now, there are a couple of these tools out there. They\'re all pretty good. They\'ll all do the job. There\'s make.com is a one that you\'ll hear a lot about, but the one that I use'

[08:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and the one that I think is still the most powerful is n8n. This allows me to put through workflows that have multi-step processes and that can run automatically that can take care of various complicated tasks. In essence,'

[08:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it\'s like having a way of creating my own software in a node-based system that does virtually anything I can think of. It connects with so many different things. As long as you\'re willing to put in the time and the patience cuz there'

[08:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is a strong learning curve towards learning n8n or even make which is a little bit easier to get started. Long as you\'re willing to put in the effort to get past that learning curve and to develop these things, I believe a automation engine is absolutely'

[09:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'essential for everybody. Even if you have a writer-based wrapper tool like Novacrafter for instance or this new tool that I\'m building myself, it\'s useful to have a understanding of how these automation'

[09:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'engines work because there may be things you want to tweak about the workflows that you get in that other tool or there might be other workflows that you want to create that have nothing to do with those tools. They are just for you'

[09:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'personally. For instance, I\'m building one right now that goes through all of the incoming news reports that I get and different newsletters about AI and kind of summarizes them and puts all of the links in a convenient way so that I can'

[09:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'very quickly go through and look through them. And it\'s just stuff like that that can be really, really useful. I also created a YouTube script generator that I used to actually monetize another YouTube channel that I have. It was an'

[09:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'experiment, so I\'m not working on it now, but I managed to monetize it in about 3 weeks, which is an insanely quick thing. The only way I was able to do that is I released a a video every day and the only reason I was able to do that is because I had a YouTube script'

[10:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generator that made the first part of the YouTube process very, very slick. But I also use it for writing as well. As you can see, I\'ve got a couple of different things here. I\'ll show you this one for instance. This is my'

[10:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'automation that takes an outline and generates chapters from that outline. And it\'s a very lengthy, multi-step process and right now the tool that I mentioned is something we\'re working on'

[10:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that actually takes what you see here and incorporates it into the tool so you don\'t have to learn all this stuff to do it. You can just click a button and it\'ll do it for you. But regardless, I think having the knowledge to build'

[10:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'something like this is an extremely valuable knowledge to have. In fact, we even have a member of my community who learned N 8 N and then got a pretty significant promotion at work because he was doing this kind of stuff for the'

[10:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'people he was working with. So, it\'s definitely a valuable tool to have and I strongly recommend it. All right, the fourth and final tool that I want to talk about today is a AI art/video aggregator. And there are a lot of these'

[11:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'out there. The one that I personally use is called Higgs Field, higgsfield.ai. There are others like FreePik that is pretty good. But Higgs Field is the one that I\'m using, it\'s the one that my buddy Akello is using and you may have seen some of his videos talking about'

[11:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Higgs Field and what you can do in Higgs Field. But basically, the value of having an aggregator like this is it kind of takes all of the major AI art and AI video models and puts them in one place so that you only have to pay one'

[11:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'subscription for access to all of them. Doesn\'t cover everything, of course. Midjourney famously does not have an API and so Midjourney is not included in one of these things. That said, Midjourney has kind of been falling behind lately and so it\'s not necessarily something'

[11:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that you\'re going to need in the future even though I still think it has really amazing aesthetics. But regardless, it\'s handy to have access to any of these models at your fingertips anytime you need them. Now, this is one thing that,'

[12:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you know, maybe you don\'t need a really expensive subscription to Higgsfield. Maybe you just need something that you could do pay as you go with Nano Banana or something like that. Maybe you don\'t have the needs for AI art or video as'

[12:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'much as you you might think. But I think once you start getting into the business side of writing where you\'re creating ad copy and ad images and you might be doing little TikToks with AI video that are based on your books. Once you start'

[12:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'getting into that stuff, it\'s really useful to have a tool like this and have some knowledge of how to use it. At the very least it can help you with your branding and making sure everything looks nice wherever you are on the internet. Like I used it for some assets'

[12:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'here that I put inside of my school community. I used it for silly stuff that I just random things that have nothing to do with my business. I\'ve been working on this little AI video for like this 8-bit character that looks'

[12:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'maybe something like me if I was a little bit more handsome and in 8-bit. And you know, lots of other things as you can see that I\'ve been using it for just various assets and including video where here\'s that video I was'

[13:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mentioning. There\'s just a lot you can do with something like this. So I strongly recommend you check it out and have access to something like that. It can save you a whole lot of time and really boost you forward especially when you get into the marketing side of your'

[13:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'books. Before we go, I want to just add a couple of honorable mentions. These aren\'t all AI tools but they\'re tools that I use regularly in my author business. First, there\'s AutoCrit, which is an AI editing tool. It\'s not all AI.'

[13:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'It didn\'t start out as an AI editing tool, but they\'ve incorporated a few AI features that have been really, really helpful over the last couple of years. Then there\'s Atticus, which is a book formatting tool. You also might use'

[13:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Vellum if you have a Mac, but a formatting tool is, in my mind, an essential piece of the publishing process. If you don\'t have a good formatter, you\'re probably going to have a hard time publishing to Amazon because your books are going to be a bad'

[13:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'experience for readers. I also have a tool called Publisher Rocket that I use very frequently for research, specifically for keyword and category research to see what are people searching on Amazon and, you know, how could I potentially fill a need like'

[14:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that on Amazon. There\'s a website called Miblart, m i b l a r t, and they are one of my go-to services for book covers. They\'re very affordable for the quality of book cover that you get. I know you'

[14:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can actually go and develop book covers on a tool like Higgsfield, for example, but I found that authors who don\'t have design experience, doesn\'t matter what AI tool they use, they end up having a'

[14:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'book that looks very unprofessional, especially when it comes to typography. Usually, that\'s where the problem is. And add to that the fact that authors don\'t always know the trends in terms of visuals on the book cover for the genre'

[14:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that they\'re writing in. Whereas, a professional designer would know those things. And so, I usually defer to a professional designer that knows what they\'re doing. And Miblart is the service that I use primarily for that. Last but not least, I want to highlight'

[15:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Suno. I added Suno as an honorable mention because it\'s not really something that authors need to have, but it is a kind of fun to have because Suno allows you to generate music, including instrumental music, which I have been'

[15:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'using pretty heavily recently to just develop soundtracks and almost like a mood board, but for your ears for the books that I create. And it\'s just been a ton of fun. So, it\'s one of those things that you like it\'s definitely not something you have to do, but I strongly'

[15:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'recommend at least playing around with it and checking it out. If you want to know my exact workflow, my exact prompts, even copies of all of the automations that I use, along with early access to the tool that I mentioned, check out my membership down below'

[15:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'called Story Hacker AI where I present to you what I truly believe to be the fastest and most affordable way to produce. We\'re talking 12 plus books a year using AI and without sacrificing your creativity or ethics. Link is down'

[15:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'below and I\'ll see you in the next video.'
